May 2024 Fundraising Report
Patryk Krasnicki

Jun 7, 2024 ⋅  14 min read

Key Insights

  • Deal volume decreased 8.8% MoM to $1.28 billion. However, the number of deals increased 0.7% MoM, sustaining near yearly high levels with 303 deals.
  • The most notable deals included Farcaster ($150 million), Polymarket ($70 million), Babylon ($70 million), Securitize ($47 million), and Humanity Protocol ($30 million).
  • The financial sector saw the most activity, accounting for 25.2% of fundraising volume with $323 million.
  • Consumer sector deal volume erupted by 248.4% MoM to $246 million. This was primarily due to a massive raise by Farcaster.

Deal volume in May 2024 decreased 8.8% MoM, falling to $1.28 billion and stagnating away from an uptrend that started in the summer of 2023. The number of deals increased 0.7% MoM, rising to 303 and holding around yearly high levels of above 300. The financial sector saw the most activity, accounting for 25.2% of fundraising volume with $323 million. The infrastructure and consumer sectors were second and third, accounting for 21.2% and 19.1% of fundraising volume, respectively.

Note: Messari is in the process of adding additional public token sale data. Thus, historical data shown in this report may deviate from previous reports.

Early-Stage Deal Trends

Early-stage deal volume stayed flat, increasing by just $2.3 million to $581 million. However, early-stage deal count fell 6.7% MoM to 97. These pre-seed through Series A deals accounted for 45.1% of total fundraising volume, with notable rounds being concentrated in the infrastructure and networks sectors.

Lagrange

Lagrange raised $13.2 million in a seed round led by Founders Fund. The protocol’s primary services include generating zero-knowledge (ZK) proofs via its ZK Coprocessor and generating state proofs via State Committees. For more information about proof generation, check out our report on ZK Coprocessors and Verifiable Compute.

The bull case: Lagrange aims to unlock new types of data-intensive and cross-chain applications by enabling verifiable computation over blockchain data. Its product suite supports cross-chain interoperability, an area in need of innovation as liquidity and user bases continue to fragment across networks.

For example, State Committee state proofs support interoperability protocols by attesting to the finality of optimistic rollup blocks once the rollup publishes data to its data availability layer. An interoperability protocol can use a proof to verify that a user has deposited funds on rollup A and then mint the corresponding funds on rollup B. These types of proving services provide value by enabling improved user experiences via interoperability protocols.

The bear case: Lagrange’s State Committee nodes, and prover nodes that attest to the ZK Coprocessor’s ZK proofs, are both secured by EigenLayer restaking. As actively validated services (AVS), nodes need to be incentivized to provide the respective services. Overall, the proof space is nascent, and while it is growing, the economics of proof generation have yet to be validated on a longer-term time horizon. Not to mention, Lagrange is set to compete with projects playing in similar spaces like Succinct, Herodotus, Union, Spectre, and Electron.

Plume Network

Plume Network (Plume) raised $10 million in a seed round led by Haun Ventures. Plume is an upcoming Layer-2 network specializing in real-world assets (RWAs). Plume will offer infrastructure for deploying assets, compliance tools, and a marketplace for activities like trading, borrowing, and lending assets.

The bull case: While Layer-2s are launching left and right, there aren’t many established networks that are hyper-specialized for RWAs. With the high level of compliance required for TradFi institutions to play onchain, compliance capabilities like identity verification built in at the network level could be enticing. Furthermore, Plume’s RWA Launcher hopes to provide a no-code tool to more easily bring RWA assets onchain, providing an avenue to onboard net-new TVL.

The bear case: While networks specializing in RWAs are a niche sector, Plume will have some competitors in the space. For example, Kinto and re.al are building similar Layer-2s focused on RWA use cases. However, it’s yet to be seen whether TradFi institutions are interested in bringing tokenized RWAs onto upstart networks like Plume over established networks like Ethereum.

Switchboard

Switchboard raised $7.5 million in a Series A co-led by Tribe Capital and Rockaway X. Switchboard provides oracle services, giving developers the tools to access onchain and offchain data feeds and integrate verifiable randomness into their protocols.

The bull case: Oracles are a critical primitive in the onchain ecosystem. After years of Chainlink dominating with its push oracles, Pyth disrupted the market with its proliferation of pull oracles. This style of oracle is only used (“pulled’) when they are needed by a protocol, often leading to reduced costs and increased efficiency. Switchboard offers both styles while focusing on providing increased customizability and extra features like Switchboard Randomness and Switchboard Secrets. With the protocol’s focus on customization and incentivized usage via the Switchboard Orbs points program, Switchboard is seeing significant traction.

The bear case: Switchboard oracle functionality is currently limited to Solana. Therefore, growth may find a stagnation point, especially if the Switchboard Orbs point program were to conclude. While the protocol has plans to launch on EVM networks, a launch date is yet-to-be announced. Even so, Switchboard could struggle to find adoption on EVM networks when it does launch. Pyth has beaten it to that market and has been carving out a market share of its own.

Financial Sector

Finance deal volume increased 16% MoM to $323 million, while deal count increased 17.8% to 86. The sector was once again dominated by investments in centralized companies. However, Polymarket, a decentralized prediction market, broke through and was the most funded project in the sector.

Polymarket

Polymarket raised $70 million in a Series A and B, led by General Catalyst and Founders Fund, respectively. Polymarket is a decentralized prediction market that allows users to bet on the outcome of events across categories like politics, sports, crypto, pop culture, business, and science.

The bull case: As seen in our report on Polymarket, it seems the protocol may be finding the elusive “product market fit.” Polygon allows users to bet on the outcomes of real-world events in a decentralized manner, such as the winner of the upcoming United States presidential election. Outside of users being able to create and bet in various prediction markets, Polymarket may serve an even greater purpose as an alternative polling system. With market probability being derived from financial incentives, Polymarket’s prediction markets could serve as an alternative, and possibly more accurate means of determining the likelihood of events. This could prove to be especially important with fake news impacting prior presidential races and deep fakes becoming ever more prevalent.

The bear case: Polymarket’s product plays in a regulatory danger zone. Recently, the CFTC proposed a ban on the trading of derivatives betting on political contests and derivatives meant to bet on elections and sporting events. Polymarket has already been fined by the CFTC as part of a settlement where it promised to wind down services in the US. Furthermore, without a token, Polymarket remains vulnerable to vampire attacks that have disrupted other tokenless projects like OpenSea.

Securitize

Securitize raised $47 million in a strategic funding round led by Blackrock. Securitize is a centralized company that facilitates private market investing, private equity funds, and alternative asset investing for individuals and businesses via tokenization of RWAs.

The bull case: Securitize made a name for itself upon the launch of BUIDL, a tokenized Blackrock fund on Ethereum that invests assets in RWAs (cash, U.S. Treasury bills, and repurchase agreements). The BUIDL token seeks to maintain a stable value of $1 and pay dividends directly to tokenholder wallets, while being usable onchain. Securitize is the transfer agent for BUIDL, which has grown to become the number one onchain RWA (excluding stablecoins). This success, name recognition, and support from Blackrock could lead to Securitize continuing to gain momentum as more RWAs come onchain.

The bear case: Onchain use cases for permissioned RWA products like BUIDL are limited. This is due to stringent compliance requirements, limiting access to the token and usage of the token within DeFi. Without the unconstrained ability to push integrations and adoption for its products, Securitize’s success may lay partially outside of its own realm of control.

Infrastructure Sector

Infrastructure deal volume increased 51.3% MoM to $273 million, while deal count decreased 22.2% to 28. The mining operations category once again experienced the most activity, though the liquid staking category saw an uptick due to a large raise by Babylon.

Babylon

Babylon raised $70 million in a Series B led by Paradigm. Babylon offers bitcoin staking, leveraging Bitcoin's security to secure proof-of-stake (PoS), Cosmos-based networks. Staked BTC remains on Bitcoin mainnet while Babylon uses cryptography and Cosmos’ Inter-Blockchain Communication (IBC) to translate the staked assets while delegating Bitcoin security in exchange for staking compensation.

The bull case: EigenLayer has been widely seen as a paradigm-shifting innovation for Ethereum and ETH the asset. It extends ether’s use by allowing staked ether to be re-used to secure AVSs. Proof of the large demand to use ETH in this manner can be seen onchain.

Babylon operates under a similar thesis, aiming to extend bitcoin’s functionality by allowing it to be staked to secure networks. As seen in our report on Babylon, this not only provides an option to earn yield for bitcoin holders but could also present improvements for networks that opt to use Babylon for security.

BTC is a more desirable asset than other network tokens. Thus, less would need to be spent on token emissions to incentivize staking than when a network token is used to secure the network. Furthermore, by leveraging the security and immutability of Bitcoin, unbonding periods could be drastically reduced from the typical 21 day periods, and the threshold needed to conduct liveness attacks could increase from one third to one half of validators.

The bear case: Babylon has several challenges that could limit its growth. First, bitcoin holders HODL, with 25% of the BTC supply being idle for over five years and 67% being idle for over one year. Many holders are averse to giving up full control of their coins. Second, due to Babylon’s technical infrastructure, it will be limited to securing Cosmos-based networks until IBC interoperability innovation allows otherwise. Lastly, leveraging Bitcoin to secure entire Layer-1 networks is unproven. The idea can work in concept and on testnet but is extremely technically complex, and true stress testing will only happen once significant value is at stake.

Cysic

Cysic raised $12 million in a pre-Series A co-led by OKX Ventures and HashKey Capital. Cysic develops specialized hardware for real-time ZK proof generation. The hardware is designed to integrate with popular frontend tools and support various ZK schemes. For more information about ZK proofs, check out our Deep Dive into Proof Marketplaces.

The bull case: With the emergence of ZK proof requestors (ZK rollups, ZK protocols, and ZK coprocessors), the ability to generate and then cryptographically prove the validity of ZK proofs is a growing need. Cystic aims to fill this need and enable faster and more cost-efficient ZK computation with their hardware. This hardware could see significant demand in an emerging space that is growing. Cysic will seek to capitalize on that demand, having stated it will use these funds to fuel global expansion, hiring, and hardware production.

The bear case: As a real-world hardware company, Cysic won’t be able to use tokens to bootstrap production. Instead, it will have to follow the Web2 model of attracting capital via equity to then be invested in its production capabilities. As mentioned previously, the proof space is nascent. While it is growing, the longer-term economics of proof generation and proving have yet to be seen. If proof generation turns out to not be highly profitable over the medium to long term, Cysic could struggle to see demand for its hardware. Especially as it competes with other ZK proof hardware providers like Ingonyama.

Consumer Sector

Consumer deal volume increased 248.4% MoM to $246 million, while deal count increased 28.1% to 41. This eruption was due to a massive $150 million raise by Farcaster. However, when excluding this deal, the sector still saw deal volume increase by 36.3% MoM, or $25.7 million.

Farcaster

Farcaster raised $150 million in a Series A led by Paradigm. Farcaster is a decentralized social protocol whose onchain infrastructure is built on OP Mainnet, and whose top application is Warpcast.

The bull case: Warpcast offers features similar to incumbent social media platforms like Twitter and Reddit, with “cast” posting, user following, and community formation via “channels.” However, it is also open-source, allowing anyone to join or develop atop the platform. For example, “Frames” allow anyone to create mini-apps akin to interactable webpages. As seen in our report on SocialFi, this has led to extended features like tipping, minting, token gates, or making purchases all within the app.

Activity on Farcaster has been on a steady uptrend since activity exploded in late January into February. This growing interest is further evidenced in May’s fundraising, which also saw Farcaster-adjacent protocols receive funding:

  • Kiosk raised $11 million in a Series A led by Electric Capital. Kiosk is developing a Farcaster client integrating social media with onchain commerce. It enables users to mint NFTs, discover and buy assets, join token-powered communities, and receive notifications about important events, all within a single application.
  • Neynar raised $11 million in a Series A led by Haun Ventures and Union Square Ventures. Neynar is a developer platform offering APIs and SDKs for interacting with Farcaster. The platform enables writing data, creating bots, managing Farcaster frames, and accessing user and feed information on Farcaster. Neynar also provides tools for setting up webhooks, managing storage, and querying data via SQL.

The bear case: While hype for SocialFi and Farcaster has grown over the past year, the category has yet to truly disrupt Web2 social media in a meaningful way. The project could struggle to attract usage outside of crypto-native users that are more familiar with the onchain experiences provided by the most popular Frames. Furthermore, social media platforms typically take off once the youngest generation gets excited about them and usage goes parabolic. While Farcaster provides novel experiences via Frames, it has yet to capture noticeable attention within the Gen Z demographic.

Humanity Protocol

Humanity Protocol raised $30 million in a seed round led by Kingsway Capital. It uses palm scanning, decentralized storage, and ZK proofs for onchain humanity verification. Humanity Protocol aims to provide a less invasive alternative to traditional biometric methods, while simultaneously allowing for ease of use via smartphones. Humanity Protocol plans to leverage the Polygon CDK to build its own Layer-2 zkEVM network.

The bull case: Humanity Protocol aims to solve a real problem within both the Web2 and Web3 worlds, fake and fraudulent activity. For example, LayerZero recently launched a sybil campaign to filter out fake users of its protocol, finding nearly 1 million sybil addresses. Elon Musk has gone on a crusade to rid X of bots. This is a problem across many industries and platforms.

Underpinned by zkProvers that will generate ZK proofs without the need to access personally identifiable information (PII), the protocol’s uses include onchain verification of asset ownership. This could enable users to mint RWA assets onchain or receive real-world credit/loans for onchain assets. Onchain games, social platforms, or protocol airdrops could more easily exclude bot activity. Universal basic income (UBI) could be distributed onchain to verified unique humans. Humanity Protocol’s potential use cases are wide in scope, and the project could provide a solution to the problems presented by fake activity.

The bear case: Humanity Protocol’s wide array of pursuable use cases could end up being a negative. These problems are hard to solve, and if the protocol seeks to develop varying proof infrastructures and attract different user bases, it could fail to specialize and attract significant usage in any one use case.

Concluding Thoughts

Capital flows stagnated as monthly crypto fundraising decreased 8.8% to $1.28 billion in May 2024. The financial sector led the month’s fundraising volume, accounting for 25.2% of it by increasing 16% to $323 million. The leading financial fundraiser, Polymarket, could see outsized attention as an alternative polling system throughout this year’s United States presidential election.

The infrastructure and consumer sectors were second and third in fundraising volume, seeing large upticks of 51.3% and 248.4%, respectively. Many await the launch of Babylon, which garnered $70 million and could enable BTC holders to earn a yield on their coins. On the consumer front, Farcaster saw the month’s largest raise of $150 million, as investors see its potential to disrupt the incumbent social media industry.
